{"type":"tool_call","subtype":"started","call_id":"toolu_bdrk_012BhK6M7mZ1KV9TavHvQDTk","tool_call":{"editToolCall":{"args":{"path":"/home/AMD/khoffmey/dev/TraceLens/evals/unit_tests_comparative/test06_conv_gap_exceeds_roofline/analysis_output_ref/comparative_analysis.md","streamContent":"<!--\nCopyright (c) 2024 - 2025 Advanced Micro Devices, Inc. All rights reserved.\n\nSee LICENSE for license information.\n-->\n\n# Vision - Comparative Analysis: MI300X vs H100\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis comparative analysis evaluates a single convolution operation (`aten::convolution`) across two traces. Trace 1 (MI300X) spends **2.0 ms** of GPU kernel time on the workload while Trace 2 (H100) completes the same operation in **0.04 ms** — approximately **50× faster**. The entire compute budget is consumed by one convolution forward pass (bf16, batch 4, 256→512 channels, 56×56 spatial, 3×3 kernel). Closing the gap on Trace 1 represents a potential **1.47–1.96 ms** savings (73–98% of E2E).\n\n| Metric | Trace 1 - (MI300X) | Trace 2 - (H100) | Difference |\n|--------|----------------------------|-------------------------------|------------|\n| Total Time | 2.0 ms | 0.04 ms | -1.96 ms (-98.0%) |\n| Compute % | 100.0% | 100.0% | 0% |\n| Idle % | 0.0% | 0.0% | 0% |\n| Exposed Communication % | 0.0% | 0.0% | 0% |\n| Top Bottleneck Category | Convolution (100%) | Convolution (100%) | — |\n\n{{PERF_PLOT}}\n\n## Compute Kernel Optimizations\n\nFindings from per-category kernel analysis (GEMM, SDPA, elementwise, etc.).\nSummaries of recommendations from Step 7 sub-agents, focused on individual kernel efficiency.\n\n### Top Operations\n\n| Rank | Category | Trace 1 Time (ms) | Trace 2 Time (ms) | % of Compute Time | Ops | Difference (ms) | Potential improvement (time, E2E %) |\n|------|----------|-------------------|-------------------|-------------------|-----|-----------------|-------------------------------------|\n| 1 | Convolution | 2.0 | 0.04 | 100.0% | 1 | -1.96 | ~1.469–1.958 ms (73.43–97.91%) |\n\n### 🔴 P1: Trace 1 convolution is much slower than Trace 2\n\n**Insight**: For the matched standard 2D convolution (bf16, 3×3, 256→512 channels), Trace 1 spends 2.0 ms of GPU kernel time while Trace 2 finishes in 0.04 ms — Trace 1 sustains only ~14.8 TFLOPS versus the 708 TFLOPS bf16 compute peak.\n\n**Action**: Align DNN library algorithm selection, fusion context, and execution configuration with Trace 2 for this bf16 3×3 convolution so Trace 1 approaches Trace 2 kernel duration; profile which forward path and workspace settings Trace 2 uses for the same signature.\n\n**Impact**: ~1.469–1.958 ms gap to target (73.43–97.91% of E2E)\n\n→ *See [Detailed Analysis: Compute kernel insights > P1](#detailed-analysis-compute-p1) for details*\n\n---\n\n## Kernel Fusion Opportunities (Experimental)\n\n> **Note:** Kernel fusion analysis is experimental.\n\nNo kernel fusion opportunities detected.\n\n---\n\n## System-Level Optimizations\n\n> **Note:** System-level analysis is exploratory. The patterns and recommendations below are under active development and may be refined as system-level analysis matures.\n\n> **Comparative note:** System-level analysis is performed on the primary trace (Trace 1) only. Cross-trace system-level comparison is not yet supported.\n\nFindings from system-level analysis (GPU utilization, memory transfer patterns,\ncommunication/compute overlap). These affect the GPU pipeline as a whole.\n\n✅ No system-level bottlenecks detected. GPU activity breakdown shows 100% computation, with negligible memcpy and communication overhead.\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Analysis\n\n### Compute Kernel Insights\n\n<a id=\"detailed-analysis-compute-p1\"></a>\n#### 🔴 P1: Trace 1 convolution is much slower than Trace 2\n\n**Identification:** The only convolution in this category is compute-bound on Trace 1 and consumes all category kernel time, while the matched Trace 2 run finishes orders of magnitude faster for the same op (source: `convolution_metrics.json` → `operations[].time_ms`, `operations[].efficiency.tflops_achieved`, `operations[].efficiency.resolved_peak_maf`, `operations[].efficiency.bound_type`; `convolution_ops.csv` → `lca_total_kernel_time_trace1_us`, `lca_total_kernel_time_trace2_us`, `delta_us (trace2 - trace1)`).\n\n**Data:**\n\n| Operation | Trace 1 Time (ms) | Trace 2 Time (ms) | Count (T1/T2) | Difference (ms) | FLOPS/Byte (T1) | Bound (T1) |\n|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|---------------|-----------------|-----------------|------------|\n| aten::convolution | 2.0 | 0.04 | 1 / 1 | -1.96 | 1368.67 | compute-bound |\n\n**Reasoning for Slowdown:** Trace 1 spends about 2.0 ms on GPU kernels for this convolution while Trace 2 completes the matched work in about 40 μs of kernel time. That is roughly 50× more kernel duration on Trace 1 than on Trace 2 for the same op name and shape. On Trace 1 the workload is compute-bound at high FLOPS/Byte, yet sustained throughput stays near 14.8 TFLOPS compared with the 708 TFLOPS peak reference for matrix bf16.\n\n**Resolution:** Converging Trace 1 toward Trace 2's execution path shortens the dominant kernel without relying on layout conversion, because measured transpose overhead is zero in this category. Matching how the library chooses the forward convolution implementation and associated workspace or dispatch options addresses the wall-clock gap directly.\n\n**Impact estimate:**\n- Low end (75% gap target): 1.469 ms savings (73.43% E2E)\n- High end (100% gap target): 1.958 ms savings (97.91% E2E)\n- Range: 1.469–1.958 ms (73.43–97.91% E2E)\n\n### Kernel Fusion Insights\n\n> **Note:** Kernel fusion analysis is experimental. Savings estimates use a roofline projection model (75-100% of peak) with 85% memory/compute pipeline overlap. Kernels without perf models use their measured trace time as-is. Actual savings depend on implementation feasibility and interaction effects.\n\nNo fusion savings estimates available.\n\n### System-Level Insights\n\nNo system-level issues detected. GPU utilization is 100% computation with no idle time, memcpy overhead, or communication blocking.\n\n---\n\n## Appendix\n\n### Model Architecture\n- **Model**: Vision\n- **Architecture**: CNN\n- **Scale**: Cannot be inferred from trace\n- **Precision**: BF16\n\n### Hardware Reference\n\n- **Platform**: MI300X\n- **Peak HBM BW**: 5.3 TB/s\n- **Peak MAF (BF16)**: 708 TFLOPS\n- **Peak MAF (FP8)**: 1273 TFLOPS\n"}}},"model_call_id":"f3657724-9c30-457f-812a-5c07f7300673-57-n2zh","session_id":"1415083f-2a1f-4988-abe9-6e5ae135413f","timestamp_ms":1777504919959}
